\begin{align*}\cos^3 \theta &= \cos \theta \cdot \cos \theta \cdot \cos \theta\end{align*}
We then apply the double angle identity. Our next factorization will be: \begin{align*}\cos^3 \theta &= \cos \theta \cdot \frac{1+\cos 2\theta}{2} \cdot \cos \theta\end{align*}
Since multiplying by a rational number does not change order, we can multiply this further. Now, let's multiply the inner two by finding a common denominator and then just expanding. We get: \begin{align*}\cos^3 \theta &= \cos \theta \left(\frac{1}{2} + \frac{1}{2}\cos 2\theta \right) \cdot \cos \theta\\
&= \frac{1}{2}\cos^3 \theta + \frac{1}{2}\cos \theta \cdot \cos 2\theta\end{align*}
We use the product identity to simplify $\cos \theta \cdot \cos 2\theta$ to $\frac{1}{2} \left(\cos 3\theta + \cos \theta \right).$ Our final factorization will be: \begin{align*}\cos^3 \theta &= \frac{1}{2}\cos^3 \theta + \frac{1}{4} \left( \cos 3\theta + \cos \theta \right)\\
